It may be noticed that the sharp line of demarcation drawn here and in similar passages between the offices of the so-called ‘faculties’ was a common feature of the philosophy of the seventeenth and eighteenth centurias, and has only been replaced in comparatively recent times by a more just appreciation of the complexity of our various mental operations and of the number of elements which go to make up some even of those psychical acts which at first sight appear the simplest.
